1 INTRODUCTION

Tennis is a sport that blends skill, strategy, and endurance, making it a fascinating topic to explore through data analysis. This project uses real-world tennis data to examine different aspects of the game and uncover patterns that may not be immediately obvious. The goal is to apply predictive modeling techniques to analyze key areas that influence the world of professional tennis. Specifically, this project will work with data from all professional tennis matches played during the 2023 season. The analysis will focus on identifying patterns and key factors that influenced player performance throughout the year. Using these insights, predictive models will be developed to forecast potential outcomes for other seasons, providing a data-driven perspective on what might shape the upcoming year in professional tennis.

1.1 Data set

The data set we will use contains a total of 49 variables, including information about tournament characteristics such as the type of tournament, the playing surface, and details about the winner and loser of each match, along with the respective results.

Observation: Instead of splitting a single dataset into two parts to train the model and then predict results, we will use two separate datasets. These datasets, while essentially similar, are differentiated by time: the training dataset consists of the most recent matches (from 2023), while the testing dataset includes matches from the previous year (2022). This approach is due to the point that tennis is highly complex, with tournament conditions varying significantly. To develop a more accurate model, I decided to train it using comprehensive data from each tournament, ensuring that all possible variables are considered.

#READ THE CSV FILES FOR THE TRAIN AND PREDICTION DATASETS
atp_data = read.csv("atp_matches_2023.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
atp_data_predict = read.csv("atp_matches_predict.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

1.2 Some data preparation

It is clear that out of the 49 variables, many are not relevant to our study. Some columns in the dataset are ID columns, while others are constant columns. These columns are excluded from our analysis as they do not contribute to building the model or making predictions. Therefore, we will conduct an initial cleaning to retain the most significant variables and provide a brief description of them. Among the 49 total variables, we have decided to retain the following 27 variables, as we consider that these are the main important ones

  • tourney_id: Unique identifier for the tournament.

  • tourney_name: Name of the tournament.

  • surface: Type of surface the tournament is played on (e.g., clay, grass, hard).

  • tourney_level: The level of the tournament (e.g., Grand Slam, ATP 1000, etc.).

  • winner_id: Unique identifier of the winning player.

  • winner_name: Name of the winning player.

  • winner_hand: Dominant hand of the winning player (right or left).

  • winner_ht: Height of the winning player in centimeters.

  • winner_ioc: Country code of the winning player (as per the International Olympic Committee).

  • winner_age: Age of the winning player at the time of the match.

  • loser_id: Unique identifier of the losing player.

  • loser_name: Name of the losing player.

  • loser_hand: Dominant hand of the losing player (right or left).

  • loser_ht: Height of the losing player in centimeters.

  • loser_age: Age of the losing player at the time of the match.

  • score: The score of the match (e.g., 6-4, 6-3).

  • minutes: Duration of the match in minutes.

  • w_ace: Number of aces served by the winning player.

  • w_svpt: Total number of service points played by the winning player.

  • w_1stIn: Number of first serves made by the winning player.

  • w_1stWon: Number of points won on the first serve by the winning player.

  • l_ace: Number of aces served by the losing player.

  • l_svpt: Total number of service points played by the losing player.

  • l_1stIn: Number of first serves made by the losing player.

  • l_1stWon: Number of points won on the first serve by the losing player.

  • winner_rank: Ranking of the winning player at the time of the match.

  • loser_rank: Ranking of the losing player at the time of the match.

2 VARIABLE SIGNIFICANCE IN MATCH OUTCOMES

In this initial section, we will conduct a series of analyses to better understand the variables that influence the determination of a winner or loser in a tennis match. By exploring these factors, we aim to identify the key elements that contribute to match outcomes. These preliminary analyses will be particularly useful later in the project, as they will inform the development of a logistic regression model (GLM). This model, which we will explain in detail at the end of the project, will allow us to predict match outcomes based on the characteristics of the players and the surface on which the match is played. By conducting these foundational analyses early on, we will gain valuable insights that will guide the training and prediction process in all the following models.

In the following analyses, we will make a distinction between two cases. The first case will involve considering all the data without taking into account the surface on which the match was played. In the second case, we will include the surface as a factor, as this will allow us to analyze whether it plays a significant role in determining the match outcome, or if, on the other hand, it is irrelevant.

Observation: As a tennis player with many years of experience, both watching and competing, I can theorize that the surface plays a more or less important role in determining match outcomes. This is why I will make this distinction in the analysis

2.1 Influence of the ranking of each player

2.1.1 Without considering the surface

The ranking of each tennis player is based on a points system, where players accumulate points as they win matches. Consequently, a playerâs ranking is proportional to their total points, with the number one ranking (and therefore the current best player) held by the player with the highest points at any given time. This suggests that in a match where, for example, the player ranked 7th faces the player ranked 23rd, the better-ranked player is more likely to win, as he is theoretically in better form over the past year.

To conduct this analysis, I will provide an R script that calculates the ranking difference between players. If the difference is positive, it will assign a value of 1, indicating that the player with the higher ranking won. If the difference is negative, it will assign a value of 0, representing a win by the lower-ranked player. Additionally, the script will generate a plot to visualize the number of victories based on whether the higher-ranked or lower-ranked player emerged victorious.

# Difference in ranking
ATP_matches$difference_rank = ATP_matches$loser_rank - ATP_matches$winner_rank

# Binary column: 1 if the difference is positive (so the loser rank is higher(worse) than the winner rank which is lower(better))
ATP_matches$better_rank_wins = ifelse(ATP_matches$difference_rank > 0, 1, 0)

# Count the victories, excluding NA values
victory_counts = table(ATP_matches$better_rank_wins, useNA = "no")

# Plotting
barplot(victory_counts, 
        names.arg = c("Lower Rank Wins", "Higher Rank Wins"), 
        col = c("red", "blue"), 
        main = "Victories Based on Player Ranking", 
        ylab = "Number of Matches", 
        ylim = c(0, max(victory_counts) * 1.1))

proportion_victories <- victory_counts / sum(victory_counts)
proportion_victories
## 
##         0         1 
## 0.3664709 0.6335291

As we anticipated, it is common for the better-ranked player to win when facing a worse-ranked opponent. We can initially assume that the probability of the player with the better ranking winning the match is approximately 63.3%. This is a very basic analysis that overlooks several key factors. One such factor is the type of surface on which the match is played (clay, hard court, or grass), as tennis can almost be considered a different sport depending on the playing surface. To address this, we will conduct the same analysis but additionally differentiate by the surface on which each match was played.

2.1.2 Considering the surface

ATP_matches$difference_rank = ATP_matches$loser_rank - ATP_matches$winner_rank

2.2 Influence of the serve

2.2.1 Without considering the surface

During a tennis match, there are key moments that can swing the victory in favor of one player or the other. However, one thing is clear: the player who serves first generally has the advantage, as they initiate the point and have the opportunity to take the lead. This leads to the assumption that players with a strong serve tend to win the most matches. While this is not entirely true, it allows us to analyze whether this statistic holds true or not.

To do this, we will study the effectiveness of playersâ serves and whether it contributes to their victory. We will introduce a new variable, which is the percentage of points in which the player serves their first serve. This variable will be calculated as the total number of first serves divided by the total number of service points played.

ATP_matches$first_serve_percentage = ATP_matches$w_1stIn / ATP_matches$w_svpt
head(ATP_matches$first_serve_percentage)
## [1] 0.6117647 0.7037037 0.6250000 0.6065574 0.5306122 0.6097561
#Percetage of the winner and the loser
ATP_matches$winner_1st_serve_percentage = ATP_matches$w_1stIn / ATP_matches$w_svpt
ATP_matches$loser_1st_serve_percentage = ATP_matches$l_1stIn / ATP_matches$l_svpt

ATP_matches$first_serve_wins = ifelse(ATP_matches$winner_1st_serve_percentage > ATP_matches$loser_1st_serve_percentage, 1, 0)

ggplot(ATP_matches, aes(x = winner_1st_serve_percentage, fill = factor(first_serve_wins))) +
  geom_histogram(position = "dodge", bins = 30, alpha = 0.7) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "blue"), labels = c("Loss", "Win")) +
  labs(title = "First Serve Percentage vs Match Outcome",
       x = "Winner's First Serve Percentage",
       y = "Number of Matches",
       fill = "Match Outcome") +
  theme_minimal()

As observed in the graph, as the effectiveness of the first serve improves, the total number of victories increases. Additionally, as mentioned earlier, the court surface often has a significant impact on match outcomes. Therefore, we will conduct this analysis while considering the different surfaces: clay, hard court, and grass. We will plot the number of victories on each surface and analyze whether there is any noticeable difference in the impact of first serve effectiveness.

2.2.2 Considering the surface

ATP_matches$winner_1st_serve_percentage = ATP_matches$w_1stIn / ATP_matches$w_svpt
ATP_matches$loser_1st_serve_percentage = ATP_matches$l_1stIn / ATP_matches$l_svpt

ATP_matches$first_serve_wins = ifelse(ATP_matches$winner_1st_serve_percentage > ATP_matches$loser_1st_serve_percentage, 1, 0)

ATP_victories = ATP_matches %>% filter(first_serve_wins == 1)

surface_colors = c("Grass" = "green", "Clay" = "orange", "Hard" = "blue")

ggplot(ATP_victories, aes(x = winner_1st_serve_percentage, fill = surface)) +

  labs(title = "First Serve Percentage in Victories by Surface",
       x = "Winner's First Serve Percentage",
       y = "Number of Matches",
       fill = "Surface") +

The distribution across the three surfaces appears to be approximately symmetrical, with a similar mean for the first serve percentage. However, the total number of victories on grass is significantly smaller compared to clay or hard courts, primarily because the grass season is considerably shorter, lasting only about one month each year.

2.2.3 Comparison between the service performance of each player

We can also examine how the quality of the winnerâs service influences the match outcome, specifically by comparing it to the service performance of the losing player. We will conduct a similar analysis to the ranking comparison, plotting the number of matches won by the player with the higher service percentage versus those won by the player with the lower service percentage.

ATP_matches_clean = ATP_matches %>%
  mutate(
    winner_1st_serve_percentage = w_1stIn / w_svpt,
    loser_1st_serve_percentage = l_1stIn / l_svpt
  )

ATP_matches_clean = ATP_matches_clean %>%
  filter(!is.na(winner_1st_serve_percentage), !is.na(loser_1st_serve_percentage))

ATP_matches_clean$better_service_wins <- ifelse(
  ATP_matches_clean$winner_1st_serve_percentage > ATP_matches_clean$loser_1st_serve_percentage,
  "Better Service Wins", 
  "Better Service Loses"
)

ggplot(data = ATP_matches_clean, aes(x = surface, fill = factor(better_service_wins))) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "blue"), labels = c("Better Service Loses", "Better Service Wins")) +
  labs(title = "Proportion of Wins Based on Service Percentage by Surface",
       x = "Surface",
       y = "Proportion of Matches",
       fill = "Result") +
  theme_minimal() +
  facet_wrap(~ surface)

service_proportions <- ATP_matches_clean %>%
  filter(!is.na(surface)) %>%  
  group_by(surface) %>%       
  mutate(total_matches = n()) %>% 
  group_by(surface, better_service_wins) %>%  
  summarize(count = n(), total_surface_matches = first(total_matches), .groups = "drop") %>%
  mutate(proportion = (count / total_surface_matches) * 100)   

service_proportions

We can observe that players with a higher first service percentage win more than 55% of the matches. This suggests that a better first serve improves the likelihood of winning against opponents. However, the impact, while notable, is not overwhelming, as tennis is a highly complex sport influenced by numerous factors.

2.3 Influence of the playerâs dominant hand

Another interesting analysis we can conduct is whether there is a significant advantage for left-handed players over right-handed ones. The motivation behind this analysis stems from the story of the tennis player Rafael Nadal, who, despite being naturally right-handed, was taught to play with his left hand by his uncle. The reasoning was that left-handed players supposedly have a greater advantage over right-handed ones. Nadal, often regarded as one of the greatest tennis players in history, is considered by many to owe part of his success to his left-handed playstyle. This raises the question of whether there is a clear superiority in being left-handed in tennis. It would be fascinating to explore if there is indeed a noticeable advantage for left-handed players or if it is more about individual skill and style.

2.3.1 Without considering the surface

To conduct this analysis, we will focus on matches where a left-handed player competes against a right-handed player. The goal is to determine which groupâleft-handed or right-handed playersâachieves a higher number of victories.

ATP_matches_filtered = ATP_matches %>%

This suggests that Nadalâs advantage and level of success are more closely related to his playing style rather than his dominant hand.

2.4 Influence of other characteristics

The objective of the following section is to perform a deeper analysis of additional characteristics that are also relevant during matches. Since these characteristics are not included in our main dataset, we need to obtain them from other sources. In this case, we will extract the new data from Ultimate Tennis Statistics. The challenge is that each new statistic comes in a separate CSV file. Therefore, we must merge the various CSVs, ensuring that the data aligns correctly despite the players not being ordered and the presence of missing information.

Once we have merged the different datasets, we can load our final dataset, called âTennis_Stats,â which contains additional statistics for nearly 250 top-ranked tennis players. Some of the statistics included are as follows.

Tennis_Stats = read.csv("Tennis_Stats.csv", header = TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
nrow(Tennis_Stats)
## [1] 245

NEW VARIABLES

  • Avg Unforced Errors: The average number of unforced errors made by a player per match.

  • Avg Winners: The average number of winners hit by a player per match.

  • First Serve Avg Return: The average success rate of returning an opponentâs first serve.

  • First Serve Avg Speed: The average speed of a playerâs first serve.

  • Return Rating: %1st serve return points won + %2nd serve return points won +%Break points converted + %Return games won

  • Second Serve Avg Return: The average success rate of returning an opponentâs second serve.

  • Second Serve Avg Speed: The average speed of a playerâs second serve.

  • Service Rating: %Aces + %Doble faults + %1st serve + % 1st serve points won + %2nd serve points won + %Break points saved + %Service games won.

Observations: We can observe by analything this new dataset that some information is missing due to the incomplete nature of the different databases. Therefore, it is important to carefully consider which analyses can be performed and what data is actually available.

2.4.1 Player classification

Once we have gathered all the new data, we can begin analyzing aspects that were previously unavailable. For instance, with this data, we can categorize tennis players into three groups:

  • âaggressiveâ = The player makes a high number of winners and unforced errors (âwinnersâ+âerrorsâ > 50%)

  • âconsistentâ = The player shows a mix of aggressive and defensive play, with a moderate number of winners and unforced errors ( 30%<âwinnersâ+âerrorsâ <50%)

  • âdefensiveâ = The player plays mainly defensive so he does few unforced errors and few winners (âwinnersâ+âerrorsâ < 30%)

# Filer the columns of Tennis_Stats
Tennis_Stats_filtered <- Tennis_Stats[, c("name", "value_winners", "value_unforced_errors")]

# The columns are percentages so we need to delete the symbol '%' (cleaning)
Tennis_Stats_filtered$value_winners <- as.numeric(gsub("%", "", Tennis_Stats_filtered$value_winners)) / 100
Tennis_Stats_filtered$value_unforced_errors <- as.numeric(gsub("%", "", Tennis_Stats_filtered$value_unforced_errors)) / 100

# Remove rows where there are players with missing information (cleaning)
Tennis_Stats_filtered <- Tennis_Stats_filtered %>%
  filter(!is.na(value_winners) & !is.na(value_unforced_errors))

# Add the percentage of winners and errors
Tennis_Stats_filtered$winners_plus_errors <- Tennis_Stats_filtered$value_winners + Tennis_Stats_filtered$value_unforced_errors

# Classify the players into the different categories
Tennis_Stats_filtered$classification <- ifelse(Tennis_Stats_filtered$winners_plus_errors > 0.5, "Aggressive", 
                                               ifelse(Tennis_Stats_filtered$winners_plus_errors < 0.3, "Defensive", "Consistent"))

# Sum the number of victories and defeats of each player
victories <- ATP_matches %>%
  group_by(winner_name) %>%
  summarise(victories = n()) %>%
  rename(name = winner_name)

defeats <- ATP_matches %>%
  group_by(loser_name) %>%
  summarise(defeats = n()) %>%
  rename(name = loser_name)

# Join the data
Tennis_Stats_filtered <- Tennis_Stats_filtered %>%
  left_join(victories, by = "name") %>%
  left_join(defeats, by = "name")

Tennis_Stats_filtered$victories[is.na(Tennis_Stats_filtered$victories)] <- 0
Tennis_Stats_filtered$defeats[is.na(Tennis_Stats_filtered$defeats)] <- 0

# Calculate the percentage of victories
Tennis_Stats_filtered$victory_percentage <- Tennis_Stats_filtered$victories / (Tennis_Stats_filtered$victories + Tennis_Stats_filtered$defeats)

# Plot the percentage of victories depending on the player classification
ggplot(Tennis_Stats_filtered, aes(x = classification, y = victory_percentage, fill = classification)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Victory Percentage by Player Classification",
       x = "Player Classification",
       y = "Victory Percentage",
       fill = "Classification") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "blue", "green")) +
  theme_minimal()

Observation (Important) :

At first glance, this result may seem confusing due to the high percentages. The sum of the three percentages should not exceed 1, as when one player wins, the other loses, meaning the total percentage should remain balanced. The issue lies in the fact that, as previously mentioned, our database âTennis_statsâ is incomplete. It only includes data from top-ranked and more prominent players, but not from every player who participated in a professional tournament (this are all the players form âATP_matchesâ). As a result, the top-ranked players, who are the ones included in our statistics, tend to win more matches than they lose. Since many of the players who lose are not classified by their playing style, this leads to inflated victory percentages. Nevertheless, this analysis remains valuable, as it allows us to observe that, to some extent, consistent players at the top of the world rankings tend to be more effective than those who play aggressively or defensively.

3.1.2 Data filtering and cleaning

In this section, we will primarily focus on cleaning the âscoreâ variable. Initially, we interpreted âscoreâ as a qualitative variable, which, although reasonable, is not the most optimal approach. The results of a tennis match are given by sets; for example, a score of 6-3 6-4 indicates that the first player won the first set 6-3 and the second set 6-4. In the case of a tie in sets, a third set would be played, resulting in a score like 6-3 4-6 6-2.

The problem is that these values cannot be directly interpreted or compared to analyze their relationship with the âminutesâ variable (match duration). Therefore, our first step will be to create three new variables: âwinner_gamesâ, âloser_gamesâ, and âtotal_gamesâ. These variables will represent the number of games won by each player throughout the match and the total number of games played in the match.

To achieve this, we will develop a function that, given the score of a match (e.g., â6-4 7-5â), splits the results by set and calculates the total number of games won by each player. The function will also account for matches that were not completed due to player retirement or other reasons. Finally, we will sum the number of games both players have done in a new variable called total_games that will represent the total amount of games played during the match.

# Function to extract the games won by the winner or loser
extract_games <- function(score, type = "winner") {
  # Handle NA, empty values, or walkover (W/O)
  if (is.na(score) || score == "" || grepl("W/O", score)) {
    return(0)  # Return 0 if score is empty or walkover
  }
  
  # Remove RET and any content inside parentheses (e.g., tiebreak scores)
  clean_score <- gsub("\\(.*?\\)|RET", "", score)
  
  # Remove any "0-0" from the sets (which usually indicates a retirement or error)
  clean_score <- gsub("0-0", "", clean_score)
  
  # Check if the format is valid (e.g., "6-3", "7-6(2)", etc.)
  valid_format <- grepl("^\\d+-\\d+( \\d+-\\d+)*$", clean_score)  
  
  if (!valid_format) {
    return(0)  # If the format is not valid, return 0 games
  }
  
  # Split the sets by space
  sets <- strsplit(clean_score, " ")[[1]]
  
  # Initialize counters
  winner_games <- 0
  loser_games <- 0
  
  # Loop over each set
  for (set in sets) {
    # Split the set by hyphen
    games <- strsplit(set, "-")[[1]]
    
    # If the set is "0-0 RET", only count the first set
    if (length(games) == 2 && games[1] == "0" && games[2] == "0") {
      next  # If it's "0-0", skip this set and do not count
    }
    
    # If it's a valid set (not 0-0 RET), count the games
    if (length(games) == 2) {
      winner <- as.numeric(games[1])
      loser <- as.numeric(games[2])
      
      # If both values are numeric, accumulate the games
      if (!is.na(winner) && !is.na(loser)) {
        if (type == "winner") {
          winner_games <- winner_games + winner
        } else {
          loser_games <- loser_games + loser
        }
      }
    }
  }
  
  # Return the total accumulated games for winner or loser
  if (type == "winner") {
    return(winner_games)
  } else {
    return(loser_games)
  }
}
# Apply the function to the dataset
ATP_matches$winner_games <- sapply(ATP_matches$score, extract_games, type = "winner")
ATP_matches$loser_games <- sapply(ATP_matches$score, extract_games, type = "loser")
ATP_matches$total_games = ATP_matches$winner_games + ATP_matches$loser_games
ATP_matches <- ATP_matches[ATP_matches$total_games != 0, ]

3.1.6 Benchmark

We will use a Benchmark model to evaluate the performance of our model and determine its quality. In this case, we will employ the simplest benchmark approach: predicting using the mean of the observed values.

# FILTER THE COLUMNS AND COMPUTE THE MEAN VALUE
ATP_matches_clean <- ATP_matches %>%
  filter(!is.na(minutes))
benchmark <- mean(ATP_matches_clean$minutes)
benchFit <- lm(ATP_matches$minutes ~ 1, data=ATP_matches)
pred.bench <- predict(benchFit, newdata=ATP_matches_predict)
R2 <- 1 - (mean(abs(ATP_matches_clean$minutes - pred.bench)) / mean(ATP_matches_clean$minutes))
R2
## [1] 0.7294071

In this case, the R2 value obtained from the Benchmark model is significantly lower (over 20% worse) than that of our linear regression model. This suggests that our regression model is notably more accurate and explanatory, providing better predictive performance compared to the simplistic benchmark approach.

3.2.5 Benchmark

We will use a Benchmark model to assess the performance and quality of our predictive model. For this purpose, we will adopt the simplest benchmark approach, as previously applied, by using the mean value of the games won by each player as the baseline prediction.

# FILTER THE COLUMNS AND COMPUTE THE MEAN VALUE FOR WINNER_GAMES AND LOSER_GAMES
ATP_matches_clean <- ATP_matches %>%
  filter(!is.na(winner_games) & !is.na(loser_games))

# Calculate the mean benchmark for winner_games
benchmark_winner <- mean(ATP_matches_clean$winner_games)
benchFit_winner <- lm(winner_games ~ 1, data = ATP_matches_clean)
pred.bench_winner <- predict(benchFit_winner, newdata = ATP_matches_predict)

# Calculate the mean benchmark for loser_games
benchmark_loser <- mean(ATP_matches_clean$loser_games)
benchFit_loser <- lm(loser_games ~ 1, data = ATP_matches_clean)
pred.bench_loser <- predict(benchFit_loser, newdata = ATP_matches_predict)
# Calculate R2 for winner_games
R2_winner <- 1 - (mean(abs(ATP_matches_clean$winner_games - pred.bench_winner)) / mean(ATP_matches_clean$winner_games))
print(paste("R2 for Winner Games:", R2_winner))
## [1] "R2 for Winner Games: 0.800556109270835"
# Calculate R2 for loser_games
R2_loser <- 1 - (mean(abs(ATP_matches_clean$loser_games - pred.bench_loser)) / mean(ATP_matches_clean$loser_games))
print(paste("R2 for Loser Games:", R2_loser))
## [1] "R2 for Loser Games: 0.62502950807999"

Explanation:

In both cases, the R2 value obtained for the benchmark model is significantly worse than in our linear regression models. Therefore, we can conclude that our models are more explanatory and predictive compared to simply estimating based on the mean.

On the other hand, we observe that the R2 value for the benchmark of loser_games is considerably worse than that for winner_games. This discrepancy arises because the loser_games variable exhibits much higher variability compared to winner_games. As a result, the accuracy of predictions using the mean as the benchmark is substantially lower for loser_games.

4 GLM

In this section, we will work with two generalized linear models. 4.1 Model 3: Aceâs

One of the most notable features of tennis is the number of Aces (serves that the opponent fails to touch, resulting in direct points) a player can achieve. In this analysis, we will examine the correlation between factors such as height, court surface type, the percentage of first serves successfully made, the number of serves executed during a match, among others. The main hypotheses are as follows: it is expected that height plays a significant role, as taller players can generate more power and accuracy in their serve, thereby increasing the likelihood of hitting an Ace. Additionally, the type of surface is anticipated to influence this probability, with grass courts being particularly favorable for Aces, as the faster bounce of the ball facilitates their occurrence.

4.2 Model 4: Logistic regression for predicting match outcomes

We will now present the model that proves most effective for analyzing and predicting the outcome of a tennis match. Our goal is to create a model capable of predicting the winner of a match based on the characteristics of the two players involved and external conditions, such as the court surface.

To achieve this, we will consider variables such as player rankings, age, height, and others. Based on the initial analyses conducted earlier in this work, we concluded that variables like player ranking and service percentage are significant factors in determining victory or defeat. However, we still need to study how these factors interact and collectively influence the final outcome. Additionally, we aim to identify which factor has the greatest overall impact on match results.

To achieve this, the first step of the model will involve training it using the variables mentioned earlier and analyzing the results obtained. The second step will focus on calculating the average values of certain variables for each player across all the matches available, such as the average percentage of first serves. Additionally, we will consider fixed factors like height, age, and the current ranking of both players to predict the final outcome. The final step will be to assess whether the predicted and actual results align as expected.

4.2.1 Understanding the âtargetâ variable and the other variables

In the section âVariable Significance for Match Outcomesâ, we already conducted a detailed analysis of how certain variables influence the outcome of a match, specifically determining victory or defeat. Therefore, this step has already been addressed, and we can save time by leveraging the insights from that previous work.

In this model, our target variable will be a binary variable called match_result, which will determine the winner of the match. If match_result equals 1, it indicates that Player A won the match, and if it equals 0, it means Player B won the match. In our case, the player that appears first (the one labeled âwinner_idâ) will be labeled as Player A and the other player (the one labeled âloser_idâ) will be labeled as Player B.

Observation ( Â¡VERY IMPORTANT! ): In our case, the player labeled as âwinner_nameâ is always the one who wins the match, as our dataset is structured this way. Our target variable âmatch_resultâ will take the value 1 if âwinner_nameâ wins and 0 if âloser_nameâ wins.

It is important to note that in our training dataset, âmatch_resultâ will always take the value 1 because, by default, âwinner_nameâ is the winning player. However, when making predictions, our model will treat âwinner_nameâ as Player A and âloser_nameâ as Player B. The model will assign a value of 0 or 1 to the âmatch_resultâ variable based on its prediction.

Subsequently, we can evaluate the modelâs error in predictions, as âmatch_resultâ should technically always predict the value 1. This is because we are providing the model with the characteristics of Player A, who we already know is the winner, and Player B, who we know is the loser.

#Create the variable 'match_result' (binary) but as explained always takes the value 1.
ATP_matches$match_result <- ifelse(ATP_matches$winner_id == ATP_matches$winner_id, 1, 0)
head(ATP_matches$match_result)
## [1] 1 1 1 1 1 1

PROBLEM:

Our model is not converging because the binary variable is only taking one value, making it impossible to compare. To fix this, I came up with the idea of treating the winner and loser variables as those of Player A and Player B in our training dataset as well. To do this, we will first define the variable match_result, which will randomly take a value of 0 or 1. If match_result takes the value 0, then the loser player will be considered Player A, and if match_result takes the value 1, then the winning player will be considered Player A. This approach makes sense because, in our tresting dataset, Player A will always be the winner of the match. Therefore, we can evaluate whether our prediction is correct (match_result = 1) or incorrect (match_result = 0).

4.2.3 Model adaptation balanced (final model)

The only remaining task is to adapt the data. If the match_result variable takes the value 0, then the loser will become Player A, and consequently, the characteristics of the loser player must be swapped with those of winner player to ensure consistency.

set.seed(123)  

# Define 'match_result' aleatory taking 0 or 1
ATP_matches$match_result <- sample(c(0, 1), size = nrow(ATP_matches), replace = TRUE)

The variable match_result now randomly determines which player is considered Player A and which is considered Player B. Additionally, based on the structure of our dataset, it also identifies the player who won the match (1 if Player A won and 0 if Player B won).

# We randomize Player A and Player B based on the value of 'match_result'.
ATP_matches <- ATP_matches %>%
  mutate(
    player_A = ifelse(match_result == 0, loser_id, winner_id),
    player_B = ifelse(match_result == 0, winner_id, loser_id),
    
    player_A_name = ifelse(match_result == 0, loser_name, winner_name),
    player_B_name = ifelse(match_result == 0, winner_name, loser_name),
    
    player_A_ht = ifelse(match_result == 0, loser_ht, winner_ht),
    player_B_ht = ifelse(match_result == 0, winner_ht, loser_ht),
    
    player_A_age = ifelse(match_result == 0, loser_age, winner_age),
    player_B_age = ifelse(match_result == 0, winner_age, loser_age),
    
    player_A_rank = ifelse(match_result == 0, loser_rank, winner_rank),
    player_B_rank = ifelse(match_result == 0, winner_rank, loser_rank),
    
    player_A_hand = ifelse(match_result == 0, loser_hand, winner_hand),
    player_B_hand = ifelse(match_result == 0, winner_hand, loser_hand),
    
    player_A_1stIn = ifelse(match_result == 0, l_1stIn, w_1stIn),
    player_B_1stIn = ifelse(match_result == 0, w_1stIn, l_1stIn),
    
    player_A_svpt = ifelse(match_result == 0, l_svpt, w_svpt),
    player_B_svpt = ifelse(match_result == 0, w_svpt, l_svpt),
    
    player_A_ace = ifelse(match_result == 0, l_ace, w_ace),
